From: Kamil Lulko <limakzagan@gmail.com>
Subject: ntdll: optional registry open-handle cache (VSTPOC_REGCACHE)

Heavy plugins re-open the same registry key chain and re-query a value
thousands of times/sec as a runtime license/component heartbeat, closing the
handles each cycle. AmpliTube 5 polls HKLM\SOFTWARE\IK Multimedia\AmpliTube 5
\UserSerial ~7000x/sec while idle: open \Registry\Machine -> SOFTWARE -> IK
Multimedia -> AmpliTube 5 -> NtQueryValueKey -> close x3 -> repeat. On Windows
the registry is in-process and this is free; under wine every NtOpenKey/NtClose
is a wineserver IPC round-trip, wrapped in sigprocmask and FEX-amplified, so it
became a constant UI-thread storm (~14000 write-syscalls/sec, idle; simpleperf:
38% of the message thread in wine_server_call -> NtOpenKeyEx/NtQueryValueKey).
Seeding the missing serial did NOT stop it -- the poll is unconditional.

With VSTPOC_REGCACHE=1 (off by default; opt-in per process) ntdll keeps
recently-opened key handles alive and returns them on re-open with no server
call; the matching NtClose on a cached key handle is a no-op (the cache owns the
handle). Borrow-counted so a handle the app still holds open is never evicted
from under it; bounded (256), and evicted unborrowed handles are really closed;
NtDeleteKey drops the handle. Only key HANDLES are cached -- value reads still
hit the server, so registry contents stay coherent. This eliminated ~93% of the
registry server calls on AmpliTube (~14000 -> ~1500 write-syscalls/sec) and the
periodic UI lag. Opens are dominant (re-open + re-close each cycle); not caching
values keeps correctness simple. Enabled by WineHostProcess for non-plugin
(e/installer) prefixes only; the delicate v-prefix JUCE plugins are left on the
stock path (unvalidated) and can opt in via wine_env.txt. (vstpoc)

diff --git a/dlls/ntdll/unix/registry.c b/dlls/ntdll/unix/registry.c
index da1c2e112c4..922bef279c1 100644
--- a/dlls/ntdll/unix/registry.c
